00:25:51,926 --> 00:25:55,981
and, uh, Elton found
an Easy-Bake Oven.

533
00:25:56,005 --> 00:25:57,390
We made cake.

534
00:25:57,414 --> 00:25:59,744
Oh, thank you, but, um
[Clears throat]

535
00:25:59,768 --> 00:26:01,637
Hey, Iris.

536
00:26:01,661 --> 00:26:02,654
Hey, guys.

537
00:26:02,678 --> 00:26:04,974
Hope: You have the cabinet open.

538
00:26:04,998 --> 00:26:06,976
With our classmates here.

539
00:26:07,000 --> 00:26:11,071
♪♪

540
00:26:11,095 --> 00:26:12,423
When did it...

541
00:26:12,447 --> 00:26:14,942
♪♪

542
00:26:14,966 --> 00:26:17,653
I mean...

543
00:26:17,677 --> 00:26:21,766
Uh, it must have come
earlier today.

544
00:26:21,790 --> 00:26:24,827
His safety isn't assured?

545
00:26:24,851 --> 00:26:26,437
Your dad's sending messages?

546
00:26:26,461 --> 00:26:28,664
You can't say anything.

547
00:26:28,688 --> 00:26:29,681
We won't.

548
00:26:29,705 --> 00:26:33,093
How do we know you won't?

549
00:26:33,117 --> 00:26:34,503
I sneak out.

550
00:26:34,527 --> 00:26:36,447
Out there?

551
00:26:36,471 --> 00:26:37,823
Regularly.

552
00:26:37,847 --> 00:26:39,492
That's how I found
the Easy-Bake Oven.

553
00:26:39,516 --> 00:26:42,119
That's why I wear the suit.
It's a TuffyStitch.

554
00:26:42,143 --> 00:26:43,937
Kids can wear 'em.
Kids can't tear 'em.

555
00:26:43,961 --> 00:26:45,531
Durable clothes from the '90s.

556
00:26:45,555 --> 00:26:46,865
Bite-proof.

557
00:26:46,889 --> 00:26:48,684
I know from
controlled experiments.

558
00:26:48,708 --> 00:26:52,630
Anyway, I-I go out there looking
for something that I lost.

559
00:26:52,654 --> 00:26:56,116
And I want to see
how our world is changing.

560
00:26:56,140 --> 00:26:59,194
Now you have my secret,
and I have yours.

561
00:26:59,218 --> 00:27:02,214
♪♪

562
00:27:02,238 --> 00:27:04,033
I won't tell.

563
00:27:04,057 --> 00:27:08,628
♪♪

564
00:27:08,652 --> 00:27:11,189
That message could mean
a lot of things.

565
00:27:11,213 --> 00:27:12,374
It could mean nothing.

566
00:27:12,398 --> 00:27:13,800
The CR's been
very up front about...

567
00:27:13,824 --> 00:27:15,911
There were more helicopters.

568
00:27:15,935 --> 00:27:18,547
Yeah, uh, Elizabeth said
they could only spare one,

569
00:27:18,571 --> 00:27:21,550
but there were five, and some
of them had shipping containers.

570
00:27:21,574 --> 00:27:23,235
You were out there?

571
00:27:23,259 --> 00:27:25,554
Why the hell didn't you...
Who cares?

572
00:27:25,578 --> 00:27:28,481
The CRM is bad,
and our dad's in trouble.

573
00:27:28,505 --> 00:27:31,836
And there's only one person
who can help us help him.

574
00:27:31,860 --> 00:27:34,580
[Walker growling]

575
00:27:34,604 --> 00:27:36,582
[Spray hissing]

576
00:27:36,606 --> 00:27:38,698
[Growling continues]

577
00:27:50,694 --> 00:27:53,173
Thanks for helping me
tag those empties.

578
00:27:53,197 --> 00:27:55,267
I like it out here.

579
00:27:55,291 --> 00:27:56,935
And if painting empties

580
00:27:56,959 --> 00:28:00,439
helps Dr. Bavolar study
their migration patterns,

581
00:28:00,463 --> 00:28:03,759
I'm happy to do it.

582
00:28:03,783 --> 00:28:05,761
It's important work.

583
00:28:05,785 --> 00:28:07,763
It is. That's why I do it.

584
00:28:07,787 --> 00:28:10,813
Yeah. That's one reason.

585
00:28:12,383 --> 00:28:14,103
You thrive on the unglamorous

586
00:28:14,127 --> 00:28:16,455
because you're still
trying to prove yourself.

587
00:28:16,479 --> 00:28:18,290
Wow.

588
00:28:18,314 --> 00:28:19,775
I thrive on the un...

589
00:28:19,799 --> 00:28:21,868
After what your parents
did to you?

590
00:28:21,892 --> 00:28:24,947
Yeah, I think so. [Scoffs]

591
00:28:24,971 --> 00:28:26,706
Man. Alright.

592
00:28:26,730 --> 00:28:30,210
You're the only one around here
doesn't realize you're aces.

593
00:28:30,234 --> 00:28:32,563
Will sure as hell thought so.

594
00:28:32,587 --> 00:28:34,790
I'm sure he still does.

595
00:28:34,814 --> 00:28:37,126
Don't think I didn't notice
you're wearing his jacket.

596
00:28:37,150 --> 00:28:39,795
Hey, he left it at my place
before he shipped out,

597
00:28:39,819 --> 00:28:42,631
so what are you gonna do?

598
00:28:42,655 --> 00:28:44,391
You miss him.

599
00:28:44,415 --> 00:28:49,304
I mean, he's off who knows where
protecting the girls' father.

600
00:28:49,328 --> 00:28:50,472
I mean, what's...

601
00:28:50,496 --> 00:28:51,807
You miss him.

602
00:28:51,831 --> 00:28:53,066
You can say it.

603
00:28:53,090 --> 00:28:55,327
Yeah. I do.

604
00:28:55,351 --> 00:28:58,047
I really do, okay?

605
00:28:58,071 --> 00:29:00,149
Felix. [Sighs] What?

606
00:29:00,173 --> 00:29:02,501
Your folks dealt you a bad hand.

607
00:29:02,525 --> 00:29:05,095
I just want you to be happy.

608
00:29:05,119 --> 00:29:06,597
You deserve it.

609
00:29:06,621 --> 00:29:08,991
And that's all
I'm trying to say.

610
00:29:09,015 --> 00:29:11,994
That's nice.
So, happy birthday, bitch!

611
00:29:12,018 --> 00:29:13,778
Izzy: <i>Felix, you copy?</i>

612
00:29:15,538 --> 00:29:17,775
Yeah, Izzy. Go for Felix.

613
00:29:17,799 --> 00:29:19,426
<i>I got Hope Bennett here
looking for you.</i>

614
00:29:19,450 --> 00:29:20,967
<i>Says it's urgent.</i>

615
00:29:22,136 --> 00:29:26,508
♪♪

616
00:29:26,532 --> 00:29:28,360
The science exchange
with the Civic Republic

617
00:29:28,384 --> 00:29:30,345
is about building trust.

618
00:29:30,369 --> 00:29:34,107
♪♪

619
00:29:34,131 --> 00:29:35,517
This is the first time

620
00:29:35,541 --> 00:29:38,353
that they've let anyone
inside their borders,

621
00:29:38,377 --> 00:29:40,798
wherever the hell
their borders are.

622
00:29:40,822 --> 00:29:42,691
♪♪

623
00:29:42,715 --> 00:29:45,194
He's breaking like 10 provisions

624
00:29:45,218 --> 00:29:46,453
of the Four Corners Agreement

625
00:29:46,477 --> 00:29:48,697
by even sending us
these messages.

626
00:29:48,721 --> 00:29:50,532
Now, we knew that
before we left.

627
00:29:50,556 --> 00:29:51,867
We talked about it.

628
00:29:51,891 --> 00:29:53,702
So what?

629
00:29:53,726 --> 00:29:56,963
He could be in danger, Felix.

630
00:29:56,987 --> 00:29:58,816
I mean, we...
We have to tell someone,

631
00:29:58,840 --> 00:30:00,375
or we have to have someone
check on him.

632
00:30:00,399 --> 00:30:03,045
He told us not to say anything
about these messages

633
00:30:03,069 --> 00:30:05,781
because we don't know what
the Civic Republic would do

634
00:30:05,805 --> 00:30:07,574
if they found out.

635
00:30:07,598 --> 00:30:09,568
He's such an idiot.

636
00:30:09,592 --> 00:30:12,312
He's probably
the smartest person alive.

637
00:30:12,336 --> 00:30:15,082
He told us not to say anything
to keep you safe.

638
00:30:15,106 --> 00:30:17,893
Alright.

639
00:30:17,917 --> 00:30:20,487
I promised him
that I'd keep you safe.

640
00:30:20,511 --> 00:30:22,397
We don't know
if he's in trouble,

641
00:30:22,421 --> 00:30:24,341
and if we did, we would
have to put our faith

642
00:30:24,365 --> 00:30:27,069
in his security detail.
And your boyfriend.

643
00:30:27,093 --> 00:30:29,829
Will is head of your dad's
security detail

644
00:30:29,853 --> 00:30:31,815
because he can handle himself.

645
00:30:31,839 --> 00:30:36,687
He can fight his way
out of anything if he has to.

646
00:30:36,711 --> 00:30:38,455
I'm sorry.

647
00:30:38,479 --> 00:30:40,524
We don't have any other choice.

648
00:30:40,548 --> 00:30:46,010
♪♪

649
00:30:52,117 --> 00:30:53,612
Hope.

650
00:30:53,636 --> 00:30:55,355
Hope, come on.

651
00:30:55,379 --> 00:30:58,433
Would you please talk to me?

652
00:30:58,457 --> 00:30:59,859
Hope, stop!

653
00:30:59,883 --> 00:31:02,287
"My safety not assured."

654
00:31:02,311 --> 00:31:03,530
That's what it said.

655
00:31:03,554 --> 00:31:04,864
That might have been
what it said,

656
00:31:04,888 --> 00:31:06,383
but it's letters and numbers.

657
00:31:06,407 --> 00:31:09,278
It could be radio static.
How can you not see this?!

658
00:31:09,302 --> 00:31:12,281
They are bad people, Iris,
and they have our dad!

659
00:31:12,305 --> 00:31:15,225
Are you talking about us?

660
00:31:15,249 --> 00:31:17,469
The Civic Republic?

661
00:31:17,493 --> 00:31:21,306
One of your Alliance partners?

662
00:31:21,330 --> 00:31:24,401
How are we bad, exactly?

663
00:31:24,425 --> 00:31:26,592
Come on. Tell me.

664
00:31:29,505 --> 00:31:33,468
You don't let anyone in or out.

665
00:31:33,492 --> 00:31:36,822
You won't let people
communicate with your people.

666
00:31:36,846 --> 00:31:38,565
Or vice versa.

667
00:31:38,589 --> 00:31:40,567
You don't tell anyone
where you are.

668
00:31:40,591 --> 00:31:42,441
And you have our dad.

669
00:31:44,687 --> 00:31:46,090
I have a daughter.

670
00:31:46,114 --> 00:31:50,577
♪♪

671
00:31:50,601 --> 00:31:52,170
She's a bit older than you guys.

672
00:31:52,194 --> 00:31:54,489
She's a soldier in the CRM.

673
00:31:54,513 --> 00:31:57,083
♪♪

674
00:31:57,107 --> 00:31:59,919
She's away from me a great deal.

675
00:31:59,943 --> 00:32:02,755
And that makes me scared
sometimes.

676
00:32:02,779 --> 00:32:04,666
Then I remember
that she's helping

677
00:32:04,690 --> 00:32:06,259
to protect the Civic Republic.

678
00:32:06,283 --> 00:32:11,431
She's helping us with
the Alliance of the Three.

679
00:32:11,455 --> 00:32:14,767
She's taking that risk

680
00:32:14,791 --> 00:32:20,106
to help us eventually
bring this world back.

681
00:32:20,130 --> 00:32:22,918
And that makes me brave.

682
00:32:22,942 --> 00:32:27,447
We have to be brave
in this life we have.

683
00:32:27,471 --> 00:32:29,449
Simply to exist now.

684
00:32:29,473 --> 00:32:33,953
♪♪

685
00:32:33,977 --> 00:32:40,124
I'm... I'm gonna tell you
something so you can trust me.

686
00:32:42,486 --> 00:32:47,300
Something that will make me
need to trust you.

687
00:32:47,324 --> 00:32:53,157
Your father is teaching in a
Civic Republic research facility

688
00:32:53,181 --> 00:32:55,767
in New York State.

689
00:32:55,791 --> 00:33:00,288
So, this... this is a coded map,

690
00:33:00,312 --> 00:33:02,982
so it doesn't show you
where in New York,

691
00:33:03,006 --> 00:33:05,060
but that watermark
and that stamp,

692
00:33:05,084 --> 00:33:08,188
that will show certain people
that I gave that to you.

693
00:33:08,212 --> 00:33:09,656
I told you.

694
00:33:09,680 --> 00:33:12,067
And if those certain people
found that out,

695
00:33:12,091 --> 00:33:15,237
I would certainly go to jail.

696
00:33:15,261 --> 00:33:17,072
We have those.

697
00:33:17,096 --> 00:33:18,498
Are you for real?

698
00:33:18,522 --> 00:33:20,075
I am.

699
00:33:20,099 --> 00:33:22,335
I also might be a bit drunk.

700
00:33:22,359 --> 00:33:25,502
How did you learn
to make champagne?

701
00:33:27,381 --> 00:33:29,342
I read a book in the Ag library.

702
00:33:29,366 --> 00:33:31,436
Wait, Felix gave you my alcohol?

703
00:33:31,460 --> 00:33:35,106
Well, he said it was a generous
gift form the Campus Colony.

704
00:33:35,130 --> 00:33:37,943
[Laughing] You really are
your father's daughter.

705
00:33:37,967 --> 00:33:40,111
You both are.

706
00:33:40,135 --> 00:33:43,690
I saw that when I landed,
you with your banner,

707
00:33:43,714 --> 00:33:46,190
you flipping me off.

708
00:33:48,218 --> 00:33:51,440
How does that make us
like our dad?

709
00:33:51,464 --> 00:33:53,050
You're brave.

710
00:33:53,074 --> 00:34:01,074
♪♪

711
00:34:02,491 --> 00:34:05,470
How'd you get out there
when she landed?

712
00:34:05,494 --> 00:34:07,973
I rode in the luggage
compartment.

713
00:34:07,997 --> 00:34:10,717
♪♪

714
00:34:10,741 --> 00:34:12,885
[Laughing] You're an idiot.

715
00:34:12,909 --> 00:34:15,313
[British accent]
I am my father's daughter.

716
00:34:15,337 --> 00:34:16,740
[Groans]

717
00:34:16,764 --> 00:34:18,467
[Normal voice]
I also need a drink,

718
00:34:18,491 --> 00:34:20,727
and the bitch in black
has all my alcohol.

719
00:34:20,751 --> 00:34:22,153
♪♪

720
00:34:22,177 --> 00:34:24,473
Dad left a bottle of brandy
in his office.

721
00:34:24,497 --> 00:34:25,898
Yes!

722
00:34:25,922 --> 00:34:28,643
♪♪

723
00:34:28,667 --> 00:34:30,234
[Both laugh]

724
00:34:32,262 --> 00:34:34,405
[Walkers growling]

725
00:34:38,010 --> 00:34:40,577
[Grunting]

726
00:34:44,941 --> 00:34:47,918
Hope: Okay, maybe that was
more than one drink.

727
00:34:55,803 --> 00:34:58,084
Iris: Hope, we slept through it.

728
00:35:08,724 --> 00:35:09,942
It's bad.

729
00:35:09,966 --> 00:35:11,108
Yeah.

730
00:35:14,213 --> 00:35:15,281
What do we do?

731
00:35:15,305 --> 00:35:17,283
Nothing.

732
00:35:17,307 --> 00:35:19,535
There's nothing we can do.

733
00:35:19,559 --> 00:35:22,306
So we just deal.

734
00:35:22,330 --> 00:35:25,934
We hope... and we wait.

735
00:35:25,958 --> 00:35:27,958
Your speech is in an hour.

736
00:35:29,244 --> 00:35:31,628
If it means anything, I think...

737
00:35:34,416 --> 00:35:36,592
I think Dad would want you to.

738
00:35:42,666 --> 00:35:44,475
[Muffled talking]

739
00:35:51,750 --> 00:35:52,983
Dr. K?

740
00:35:58,607 --> 00:36:00,344
[Slow music on record skipping]

741
00:36:00,368 --> 00:36:08,368
♪♪

742
00:36:09,693 --> 00:36:11,838
[Growling]

743
00:36:11,862 --> 00:36:19,862
♪♪

744
00:36:19,945 --> 00:36:27,871
♪♪

745
00:36:27,895 --> 00:36:35,895
♪♪

746
00:36:36,052 --> 00:36:44,036
♪♪

747
00:36:44,060 --> 00:36:51,750
♪♪

748
00:36:56,356 --> 00:36:58,977
And the message
I am here to deliver

749
00:36:59,001 --> 00:37:03,556
on behalf of the Civic Republic
on this your 10th Monument Day

750
00:37:03,580 --> 00:37:05,391
is one of solidarity.

751
00:37:05,415 --> 00:37:10,989
The Civic Republic stands
with Portland, with Omaha,

752
00:37:11,013 --> 00:37:14,425
and with you, the Campus Colony.

753
00:37:14,449 --> 00:37:19,814
You have loaned us
your greatest mind,

754
00:37:19,838 --> 00:37:22,408
Dr. Leo Bennett,

755
00:37:22,432 --> 00:37:25,487
who will bring other great minds
on a journey

756
00:37:25,511 --> 00:37:30,750
to create the science
that will bring this world back.

757
00:37:30,774 --> 00:37:35,346
And it's trust we've built
that allows this to happen.

758
00:37:35,370 --> 00:37:39,901
No one has given us more trust
than Leo's two daughters.

759
00:37:39,925 --> 00:37:43,913
And it's my honor now
to introduce one of them.

760
00:37:43,937 --> 00:37:47,266
She is Monument High
Student Council President

761
00:37:47,290 --> 00:37:50,603
and future scientist
Iris Bennett.

762
00:37:50,627 --> 00:37:52,769
[Applause]

763
00:38:04,641 --> 00:38:05,991
[Sighs]

764
00:38:06,977 --> 00:38:09,036
Representatives from our...

765
00:38:10,981 --> 00:38:12,458
Uh, our...

766
00:38:12,482 --> 00:38:18,798
♪♪

767
00:38:18,822 --> 00:38:25,137
♪♪

768
00:38:25,161 --> 00:38:27,899
I have these dreams
that I'm dead.

769
00:38:27,923 --> 00:38:29,859
I don't talk about them.

770
00:38:29,883 --> 00:38:32,887
The person who was helping me,
she's gone.

771
00:38:32,911 --> 00:38:37,316
And the last thing she told me
is that it's up to me now.

772
00:38:37,340 --> 00:38:39,077
♪♪

773
00:38:39,101 --> 00:38:41,913
And I guess that's growing up...

774
00:38:41,937 --> 00:38:46,568
When the person in charge
of your life is... you.

775
00:38:46,592 --> 00:38:49,921
When I'm in these dreams [Sighs]

776
00:38:49,945 --> 00:38:53,183
I feel like I've always been
in them, like I was never alive,

777
00:38:53,207 --> 00:38:56,261
like I never made it to now,
let alone the future.

778
00:38:56,285 --> 00:38:59,097
The Night the Sky Fell,
I was just a little kid,

779
00:38:59,121 --> 00:39:04,027
and I just jumped
to living for the future.

780
00:39:04,051 --> 00:39:06,345
I think a lot of us did.

781
00:39:06,369 --> 00:39:08,940
And what I figured out...

782
00:39:08,964 --> 00:39:12,594
I have to start with now.

783
00:39:12,618 --> 00:39:16,914
And I think "now"
starts with the truth.

784
00:39:16,938 --> 00:39:19,267
And the truth is...

785
00:39:19,291 --> 00:39:25,123
♪♪

786
00:39:25,147 --> 00:39:27,033
...I don't trust you.

787
00:39:27,057 --> 00:39:28,626
I don't know who you are.

788
00:39:28,650 --> 00:39:31,946
I-I don't know
what you're doing.

789
00:39:31,970 --> 00:39:34,558
You will.

790
00:39:34,582 --> 00:39:36,467
Your father does.

791
00:39:36,491 --> 00:39:40,379
Someday you will understand.

792
00:39:40,403 --> 00:39:42,548
That's just not good enough.

793
00:39:42,572 --> 00:39:46,403
♪♪

794
00:39:46,427 --> 00:39:51,575
Science is about finding the
truth, not just deciding on it.

795
00:39:51,599 --> 00:39:54,060
And that... that's...
That's hard.

796
00:39:54,084 --> 00:39:56,580
That's... That's scary.

797
00:39:56,604 --> 00:40:00,733
Because it means admitting that
we don't have all the answers.

798
00:40:00,757 --> 00:40:02,660
And we don't know
